I saw this on the internet & thought I'd pass it along.... . Eating fish does contribute to your intelligence , particularly before and just after you're born . A researcher at the University of Connecticut has found that some fish are high in a certain chemical that's vital to brain and nerve cell growth in fetuses and newborns . Babies can't make enough docahexanoic -- or DHA -- a fatty acid that helps the brain develop . They must take whatever their mothers give them , either through the umbilical cord or by breast-feeding after they're born . And note that baby formula isn't fortified with DHA . Women who eat cold-water species , like salmon , trout , sardines and tuna , give their babies a better chance at maximizing brain tissue development , the research found . Other fish high in the chemical are herring , swordfish and mackerel .
