As per our telephone call .
Any chance this language came from a credit facility that provides for the issuance of letters of credit ?
Seems to me that L/C's are the way to go then , rather than asking for cash or another asset as collateral . ( Another option would be to mix and match - taking cash up to $10 mil . and L/C's beyond that. ) Lenders frequently set up the facilities available to the borrower this way so they keep control over how much "debt" is supported by the asset base while still giving the borrower some flexibility . As you can imagine , most other extenders of credit are willing to take the bank's L/C in lieu of a lien on a hard asset .
