The Word of the Day for April 6 is: 1 a : the food of the Greek and Roman gods b : the ointme or perfume of the gods *2 : something extremely pleasing to taste or smell 3 : a dessert made of oranges and shredded coconut Example sentence: "We feasted that evening as on nectar and ambrosia; and n the least delight of the entertainment was the smile of gratification with which our hostess regarded us , as wesatisfied our famished appetites on the delicate fare she liberally supplied." ( Charlotte Bronte , Jane Eyre ) Did you know ? "Ambrosia" literally means "immortality" in Greek; it is a derivative of the Greek word "ambrotos," meaning "immorta which combines the prefix "a-" ( meaning "not" ) with ( meaning "mortal") . In Greek and Roman mythology , only immortals -- gods and goddesses -- could eat ambrosia . Th mythological gods and goddesses also drank "nectar," whicin its original sense , refers to the "drink of the gods." ( Even today , you'll often find the words "ambrosia" and "nectar" in ea other's company. ) While the "ambrosia" of the gods prevented death , we mere mortals use "ambrosia" in reference to thi that just taste or smell especially delicious .
