The Word of the Day for May 19 is: *1 : of , relating to , or caused by witchcraft or the supernatural : magical 2 : of strange or extraordinary character : odd , fantasti Example sentence: "Hagar , the witch , chanted an awful incantation over her kettleful of simmering toads , with weird effect." ( LouisaMay Alcott , Little Women ) Did you know ? You may know today's word as a generalized term for anyth unusual , but "weird" also has older meanings that are mor specific . "Weird" derives from the Old English noun "wyrd essentially meaning "fate." By the late 8th century , theplural "wyrde" had begun to appear in texts as a gloss for the Latin name for the Fates -- three goddesses who spun , measured , and cut the thread of life . In the 15th and 16t centuries , Scots authors employed "werd" or "weird" in th phrase "weird sisters" to refer to the Fates . William Shakespeare adopted this usage in Macbeth , in which the "weird sisters" are depicted as three witches . Subsequent adjectival use of "weird" grew out of a reinterpretation of the "weird" in Shakespeare .
